@DATABASE amigaguide.guide
@WORDWRAP

@NODE MAIN "Odyssey Guide"

This is a guide to the amiga data analysis package, Odyssey.

@{"Introduction" LINK INTRODUCTION}
@{"Installation" LINK INSTALLING}
@{"Requirements" LINK REQUIREMENTS}
@{"Modes" LINK MODES}
@{"Commands" LINK COMMANDS}
@{"Maths functions" LINK MATHS}
@{"Registration" LINK REGISTRATION}
@{"Author" LINK AUTHOR}
@{"Version" LINK VERSION}
@{"Help" LINK HELP}

@ENDNODE

@NODE INTRODUCTION

During my PhD, I have often generated files of data from which I need to fit curves, tidy up, extend etc.
The data come out of the experiments in columns, and spreadsheets tend to only act on cells without a lot of messing around with fill down etc.
So I have wanted a program to open these files, act column by column, do data fits etc.  Now there are several on Mac and PC, but nothing like it on the Amiga.
Well, having been bored out of my mind by our Mac Plus (or even LCII) trying a curve fit (or screen update!), I naturally wanted to use my Amiga, which is, of course, much faster - especially with FPU :) which can make a real difference here.

Odyssey is a command line driven data analysis program. It can load data files (ASCII) and manipulate @{i}columns@{ui} of data.
Note it is @{b}not@{ub} a spreadsheet - it does not act on specific cells, and has only rudimentary editing facilities.
It can select data, smooth (improve!) such, and prepare and save out columns of data for plotting packages.  It can also fit data to linear, exponential or polynomial forms, or even to any general formula you care to specify - tries anyway.
Oh, it can also be used as a calculator.

Just for fun, and a convenient reference, I have also added a few simple little maths routines, just for fun - statistics, (simple) numerical differentiation, significance tests...

This is my first ever publicly released program, before you start gleefully pointing out each and every glitch...
It has therefore been quite an ordeal producing this, especially as I had no previous experience of C programming, or indeed creating any program of this size.
Certainly it is a useful and enjoyable (mostly) challenge, and I've learnt a great deal so far.
I hope you enjoy Odyssey, maybe even find it quite useful. If not, why not try producing something similar yourself - possibly even with a GUI!

@ENDNODE

@NODE MODES

Odyssey can be thought of as running in two modes, calculator mode and data analysis mode - although both run together.

@ENDNODE

@NODE COMMANDS

There are commands for file handling, function analysis, data handling and curve fitting, maths and probability/statistics.
And undoing the mess you just made with the previous commands!

@{"Files" LINK FILES}

@{"Data" LINK DATA}

@{"Fitting LINK FITTING}

@ENDNODE


@NODE MATHS

There are many maths functions available - it is a calculator, after all.

@{"Trigonometry" LINK TRIG}
@{"Logarithms" LINK LOGS}
@{"Coordinates" LINK COORDINATES}
@{"Probability" LINK PROBABILITIES}
@{"Functions" LINK FUNCTIONS}
@{"Constants" LINK CONSTANTS}

To use them, just type in an equation, starting with '='
e.g. =5-2+sin(3)
or to assign to a variable, m0=3-2.1

Can use scientific format e.g. 2e4 = 20000 = 2 x 10^4

@ENDNODE

@NODE TRIG

Note that all angles are in @{i}radians@{ui}

The following functions are available:
sin, cos, tan,
 and inverses: asin, acos, atan

hyperbolic: sinh, cosh, tanh,
 and inverses: asinh, acosh, atanh.

e.g. sin(3.1), atanh(m1)

Can convert angles radians to degrees - deg(3.14159) = 180
 or vice versa with rad()

The constant Pi is defined in the program:
>=pi

@ENDNODE

@NODE LOGS

The following functions are available:

Exponential - exp()
Natural log - ln()
Log base 10 - log()
Log with another base - logb()
    e.g. log of x to base n = logb(x,n)
@ENDNODE

@NODE COORDINATES

Conversion of coordinates
    rectangular to polar - rp
    polar to rectangular - pr

Set x (or r) in M0
Set y (or theta) in M1
After typing rp (pr), the associated values are displayed, and copied to M0 and M1

@ENDNODE

@NODE PROBABILITIES

Factorials are taken by fact(integer) - real numbers are truncated to an integer form.

Factorials are used in permutations and combinations:

    Perm(n,r)  = n!/(n-r)!

    Comb(n,r)  = n!/(n-r)!r!

The probability of lying with a number of standard deviations of the mean in a normal distribution is given by -
Gaussian lower upper (+- number of standard deviations)

Sig or significance gives the probability of getting a result by chance, given an initial guess/assumption of the probabilities.

Rand(n) - generates and random number, 0-n.

@ENDNODE

@NODE FUNCTIONS

Functions are entered by preceding by 'f=' e.g. f=m0+2
In functions, m0 and x are equivalent, and treated as the independent variable in operations on functions.

Once a function has been entered, operations can be performed on them:

Func: the value of the function, for a specified value of x
Integrate:  simple numerical integration of function with respect to x(m0), between limits
Sum, Product: of a series of values for x
Fzero: the value of x where the function has zero value
@ENDNODE

@NODE CONSTANTS

Constants:
K0-K9: Constants for user to define and use
M0-M9: Memory locations which are modified by many operations e.g. curve fits
N0-N9: Memory locations which are modified by some operations e.g. errors in curve fits
Pi:    Set to the value of Pi
C0+:   Refer to columns, in formulae which relate columns on a row by row basis.
@ENDNODE

@NODE FILES

You can OPEN and SAVE files, reserve file space - FILE.
ASCII files can be opened - both amiga and PC definitions of ASCII: use tabs to separate columns of data and Return to end a row of data. The first few rows of data may be ignored.
If the first row contains titles, they will be loaded as such; these can be edited these later, if necessary.
These files can be typed in with any editor (though I find that ed tends to add too much junk to the file - AMOS moaned about this too), or generated direct e.g. my lab experiment saves data direct from experiment to disk (on a Mac Plus at that).

They can be set up directly, and saved to disk (saveas) - up to 6 files can be open within Odyssey at any one time (0-5)..
To use, type FILE <n> to set up the file, e.g. file 2
To create columns and rows, use setcols <c> and setrows <r>, with up to 20 columns and 600 rows.
Give titles to the columns - e.g. title c0 Temperature
After creating some data:
   >series c0 1 1 1
   >c1=2*c0+1
Save the file e.g. saveas ram:file1 2


Current parameters (M0-M9) are saved by PARAMSAVE

BATCH files can contain a set of instructions to be executed sequentially, like AmigaDOS scripts.
Can use do loops - repeat several times
do 5 lab
    instructions in loop
label loop

; - rest of line is ignored (useful in batch files)

*command - command is passed to shell/cli of AmigaDOS to execute
Note - output to screen is lost unless started from Shell or follow command with '> *'
@ENDNODE

@NODE DATA

Operations are performed on @{i}columns@{ui} of data, rather than individual rows as in spreadsheets. Although individual cells can be edited, the intention is that data is generated outside Odyssey, and manipulated (for plotting/fitting) within.
Full statistics of a column are generated via the stats command, and data can be @{b}smooth@{ub}ed, certain values @{b}pick@{ub}ed, and operations @{b}undo@{ub}ne

@ENDNODE

@NODE FITTING

With an open data file, the relationship between 2 columns can be investigated by fitting to the following forms:
@{"Linear" LINK LINEAR}
@{"Exponential" LINK EXP}
@{"Logarithmic" LINK LN}
@{"Power" LINK POWER}
@{"Polynomial" LINK POLY}
@{"General" LINK GENERAL}

All these make use of the constants M0,M1,M2... (and modify them, so @{i}beware@{ui}
The quality fit is given by the correlation coefficient R and/or chi squared.

@ENDNODE

@NODE LINEAR

Linear curve fitting

y=ax+b or y=M1x+M0

A simple and quick method based on a least squares fit.
@ENDNODE

@NODE EXP

Exponential curve fitting

y=exp(ax+b) or y=exp(M1x+M0)

A simple and quick method based on a least squares fit.
Note that this form is easily transformed to y=c.exp(dx)
@ENDNODE

@NODE LN

Logarithmic curve fitting

y=a.ln x + b or y=M1.ln x + M0

A simple and quick method based on a least squares fit.
@ENDNODE

@NODE POWER

Power curve fitting

y= a.x^b or y=M0+x^M1

A simple and quick method based on a least squares fit.
@ENDNODE

@NODE POLY

Polynomial curve fitting

y=M0 + M1.x + M2.x^2...

Fits to an order of x, up to 9. A good general purpose fit, easy to differentiate or integrate later.

@ENDNODE

@NODE GENERAL

General curve fitting

y=f(M0; M1,M2,M3...)

Type in formula f= function of M0(=x) and parameters M1, M2 etc.
The values of these parameters are modified so as to minimise chi squared between the function and the data.
This process is slow and often misleading, but so are all these methods. It is quite versatile, though.

@ENDNODE

@NODE REQUIREMENTS

This should run on any Amiga (1.2 or less, maybe?) - no fancy graphics, just good solid command lines. 512k should be sufficient, but may restrict the number of files you may have open at once.

@ENDNODE

