@NODE VERSION

This is my first release of Odyssey (June 95) so I have little experience of how it runs on different systems. I have tried to test it as best I can, anyway. It might not be too stable when fed dodgy data files etc. so beware.
It has worked all right on my A1200 so far, but you can never tell. If you have any comments, feel free to contact @{"me" LINK AUTHOR}, but remember, you get what you pay for, and this is free!

To check version when running Odyssey to determine the version number, author, etc.

@ENDNODE


@NODE HELP

Help is available for your odyssey into data analysis; apart from this guide there is on line help with Odyssey (i.e. when you need it).

@{"Installing" LINK INSTALLING} and running is easy and covered in this guide.
There is on line help for the odyssey command set.

As in AmigaDOS, typing a command followed by '?' will produce the template for the command, hence you can see at a glance the parameters taken, and their type and order.

And similar to Unix, manual pages for each command exist - just type 'man command' to get more detailed information on a command.

I have included a few example scripts/batch files.
To run them from Odyssey, just type 'batch <full path>' e.g. batch loop.batch assuming you have the examples alongside the Odyssey program. Then enter in Odyssey e.g. 'batch formula.batch'
Following through these (comments are included) should help you to use Odyssey.
@ENDNODE

@NODE INSTALLING

Installing is easy, just copy the file Odyssey to the desired directory, and the examples if you wish to use them.
Then open a shell, and type odyssey.

Do make sure that odyssey is in your current path though.

There may be 2 versions - Odyssey.881 requires a floating point unit and accelerator (i.e. 68020 or above). It is optimised to take advantage of such - although it is wonderfully fast anyway, of course!!!
The other should work on any machine - so long as it is an Amiga.
Actually I have this working on PC-DOS and Unix at the lab but as I @{i}own@{ui} neither the machines nor compilers I have no intention of releasing these versions - they are well catered for anyway.

Workbench @{"requirements" LINK REQUIREMENTS} - I think any version should suffice - for all the graphics I've put in so far :)

An editor will be required if you wish to type in data extensively, and a plotting program (there are several PD ones around) will also be useful.

@ENDNODE

